WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.600
Hi everybody, I'm going to be sharing today about documenting things and how doing this

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:19.940
with intention can really help big organizations do hard things around tech and culture.

00:00:19.940 --> 00:00:27.480
So I'm Julie Lowndes, I am a marine ecologist and I grew up in the R and open science communities

00:00:27.480 --> 00:00:34.380
and documenting things has been a big part of my shift towards doing my own research

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:39.160
to supporting other research teams doing research.

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:44.680
And so I do that now through a program called Openscapes and this is a huge collaborative

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:51.139
effort with many, many people I'm going to be sharing from.

00:00:51.139 --> 00:00:55.040
So let's talk about documenting things openly for future us.

00:00:55.040 --> 00:00:58.959
So first of all, things is all of the things.

00:00:58.959 --> 00:01:05.360
This is your code and analyses, your teaching resources, your onboarding and community documentation,

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:09.599
your field work, your lab notebooks, events that you've got, your blog posts, like you

00:01:09.599 --> 00:01:10.959
name it.

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:17.480
And future us is really a mindset and a habit around the idea that you're doing this work

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:23.320
for yourself, for ourselves, for our teams, for our communities and really thinking about

00:01:23.320 --> 00:01:28.360
that on different time scales in the next hour, in the next week, in the next decade.

00:01:28.360 --> 00:01:32.879
So this is really getting beyond the idea of working by yourself on your own laptop

00:01:32.879 --> 00:01:37.279
and really thinking about how to be intentional and inclusive in the work that you do so that

00:01:37.279 --> 00:01:40.720
others can benefit as well.

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:43.080
So documenting things does not have to be painful.

00:01:43.080 --> 00:01:46.440
That's one of the things I'd like to share today.

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:48.360
And in fact, it's supposed to be helpful.

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:52.879
It's supposed to be there for you so that you're not having to repeat the same mistakes

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:57.000
or frustrations that you or others have had in the past.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.279
It does, however, take time and intention.

00:02:00.279 --> 00:02:06.639
It takes support of yourself and others, and it really means kind of slowing down briefly

00:02:06.639 --> 00:02:12.279
in order to speed up for yourself and others over the long term.

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:16.240
So really the purpose today is to help you document things effectively and also hear

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:22.559
stories about how documentation can be visible and valued and help teams be efficient, productive,

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:24.000
and less lonely.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.600
So the structure of this talk is going to be a five-minute lightning talk with practical

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.440
tips, and this is inspired by Jenny Bryan's Naming Files.

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:35.759
And Jenny Bryan has been such a role model and teacher about how to document things well

00:02:35.759 --> 00:02:40.479
and share with others, and so I'm trying to bring some of that here.

00:02:40.479 --> 00:02:45.199
And then we'll have 10-minute stories about repeatable strategies from community organizations

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:48.339
at NASA and other places.

00:02:48.339 --> 00:02:51.119
So let's get started.

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:53.039
Have a place.

00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:57.559
Have an audience in mind designed for readability and accessibility.

00:02:57.559 --> 00:02:58.720
Have a place.

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:00.240
It doesn't matter where at first.

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:01.240
Just write it down.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:03.520
Write it down somewhere, some kind of software you're using.

00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:04.520
Get it.

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:05.520
Get it.

00:03:05.520 --> 00:03:07.600
Have a place there.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.559
Then having that place will let you write as you go.

00:03:10.559 --> 00:03:14.960
You'll be able to develop a habit of writing things in that place, and one of the ways

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:18.039
you'll do that is by copying and pasting things you're already writing.

00:03:18.039 --> 00:03:20.679
Take it from that Slack message, that email.

00:03:20.679 --> 00:03:24.399
This will help you break down documentation that otherwise can seem like a big looming

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:28.080
task that might take weeks to do.

00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:34.000
Keyboard shortcuts are great for cutting and pasting text from one place to another.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:36.520
You'll be able to write in a modular way.

00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:42.559
Writing in small bits is less daunting, and it's easier to maintain collaboratively.

00:03:42.559 --> 00:03:47.080
You'll be able to write these little bits in a way that can be networked so that you

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:51.960
can link back and forth to them because you don't need a linear flow when you're writing

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:52.960
documentation.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:56.639
This will also help you follow the concept of don't repeat yourself, which is something

00:03:56.639 --> 00:04:00.039
that we can borrow from coding, where you're trying to have your code only written once

00:04:00.039 --> 00:04:02.259
that you call by functions.

00:04:02.259 --> 00:04:06.440
There's often also no true order to what you're documenting, and so you'll be moving things

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:09.199
around as you develop.

00:04:09.199 --> 00:04:11.839
Having an audience in mind is key here.

00:04:11.839 --> 00:04:17.160
You're writing this for someone, that someone is probably you and many others, and different

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:21.679
audiences at different entry points, so you can make your documentation engaging.

00:04:21.679 --> 00:04:25.480
It doesn't have to be dry or distant.

00:04:25.480 --> 00:04:30.600
Writing in an inclusive tone is part of this, and having the mindset of we're in this together

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:34.720
and that your readers are intelligent people and they're here, and they're here to learn

00:04:34.720 --> 00:04:35.720
from you.

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:39.559
So you can really consider your goals for your documentation and the style that you

00:04:39.559 --> 00:04:42.000
want to have that can welcome readers.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.880
You can avoid specific words that trivialize pretty complex things, like simply clone the

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:48.880
repo.

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:53.200
There's a lot to unpack in a statement like that, and thinking about how to meet folks

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:54.760
where they are.

00:04:54.760 --> 00:05:00.640
There's a lot of thoughtful resources that you can emulate, and these are just a few.

00:05:00.640 --> 00:05:03.920
Narrate code in small chunks if you're presenting code.

00:05:03.920 --> 00:05:09.239
So this is you can narrate your code in a way that you would say it out loud if you

00:05:09.239 --> 00:05:14.320
were teaching it, and you can match that tone with your purpose, especially as you're trying

00:05:14.320 --> 00:05:18.640
to highlight specific parts of your code for learners to focus on.

00:05:18.640 --> 00:05:22.959
We learned this morning that Cuarto has a new code annotation feature to help in this

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:25.799
as well.

00:05:25.799 --> 00:05:29.100
Sharing early is a big part about writing documentation.

00:05:29.100 --> 00:05:33.320
You want to be able to have this be useful for folks as soon as possible, and you want

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:38.480
to be able to iterate it and receive feedback and incorporate that feedback to improve it.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:43.359
This is where the idea of open comes in, and open does not need to mean public.

00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:49.119
Open can mean shared with your team, and you're able to leverage different technologies and

00:05:49.119 --> 00:05:53.739
the permissions that come with them so that you can share what you want broadly and also

00:05:53.739 --> 00:05:55.079
keep things private.

00:05:55.079 --> 00:05:58.799
I think about this as leaving breadcrumbs for yourself, and in this example, this is

00:05:58.799 --> 00:06:03.119
a public Cuarto documentation for NOAA fisheries where they're still able to include internal

00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:08.399
links that are just accessible to them, but we're all able to benefit from this documentation.

00:06:08.399 --> 00:06:12.320
Lastly, design for readability and accessibility.

00:06:12.320 --> 00:06:17.040
And we're able to leverage a lot of defaults on the software side and best practices on

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:22.720
the community side in order to support these goals.

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:26.279
Using section headers is one thing we can do here.

00:06:26.279 --> 00:06:31.679
These are important for screen readers to help describe the sections and flow of a document,

00:06:31.679 --> 00:06:36.239
and you're able to anchor to them directly so that you're able to share a URL specifically

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:39.040
anchored to a certain section of your documentation.

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:44.119
Naming things can be really key here, and you're able to embrace the idea of the slug

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:49.119
where the name of the header becomes the URL so that you're able to give a little bit more

00:06:49.119 --> 00:06:52.279
information about what that header is.

00:06:52.279 --> 00:06:54.640
Use text formatting in your documentation.

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:57.320
This will help your readers follow along.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:07:01.220
You're able to hyperlink to the thing that is important for people to look at rather

00:07:01.260 --> 00:07:06.660
than a word like here or this that can be ambiguous and hard to see as well.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:13.920
You're also able to distinguish code with fonts and use markdown in this case as well.

00:07:13.920 --> 00:07:17.100
Using alternative text for images is really important.

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:22.540
This is something that describes the details of the take home messages of the visuals.

00:07:22.540 --> 00:07:28.459
So it's different from a caption in that it will actually describe that a round hedgehog

00:07:28.459 --> 00:07:34.660
is knitting a yellow sock, a rabbit with a teal beanie is wearing one yellow sock,

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:39.179
and it watches in anticipation, and a shelf to the left of them contains yarn in a tote

00:07:39.179 --> 00:07:45.260
labeled text, and knitting patterns in that tote are labeled code.

00:07:45.260 --> 00:07:50.619
So that concludes the lightning talk about documenting things.

00:07:50.619 --> 00:07:55.500
And I want to now shift to what's possible about this and tell a few stories about our

00:07:55.500 --> 00:07:58.779
work with Openscapes.

00:07:58.779 --> 00:08:05.059
So putting a focus on documentation has enabled NASA to collaborate across divisions and support

00:08:05.059 --> 00:08:08.619
users that are transitioning to Earth Data Cloud.

00:08:08.619 --> 00:08:14.540
So as a reminder, NASA collects an amazing amount of data about our Earth.

00:08:14.540 --> 00:08:18.140
They have many satellites and missions that are collecting data that are freely available

00:08:18.140 --> 00:08:22.739
for users who are studying our planet, who are studying climate change, who are studying

00:08:22.739 --> 00:08:28.619
public health, agriculture, sea ice melt, a lot of awesome and important work.

00:08:28.619 --> 00:08:34.979
And these data have been traditionally downloaded by researchers in order to do analyses locally.

00:08:34.979 --> 00:08:40.340
And after many years of effort and planning, these data are being migrated to the cloud

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:46.140
in AWS West 2, and this means that researchers are going to be taking their compute to the

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:49.059
cloud in order to analyze these data.

00:08:49.059 --> 00:08:54.659
This means that this is a big shift in the way researchers have worked their entire careers,

00:08:54.659 --> 00:09:00.380
and it's also a shift for the NASA staff who support researchers in terms of how they teach

00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:04.179
users to access and work with these data.

00:09:04.179 --> 00:09:10.020
And this teaching this NASA Earth Data Cloud is going on by learning as a community as

00:09:10.020 --> 00:09:11.340
we go.

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:19.059
So the NASA Openscapes project is a project that I lead with my co-lead, Aaron Robinson,

00:09:19.059 --> 00:09:25.500
and we are supporting a mentor group across the NASA Earth Science Data Centers, and those

00:09:25.500 --> 00:09:32.679
folks are creating and teaching common tutorials that researchers are using to migrate their

00:09:32.679 --> 00:09:35.059
analytical workflows to the cloud.

00:09:35.059 --> 00:09:40.859
So this is a huge effort around connecting folks from different parts of an organization,

00:09:40.859 --> 00:09:45.419
having them be in a comfortable environment to learn together, to teach together, to write

00:09:45.419 --> 00:09:47.700
documentation together.

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:55.140
There's a lot of emphasis that we put on building a psychologically safe space to ask questions,

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:59.340
to have a growth mindset where we're able to learn and do together.

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:03.820
What I'm not going to talk about today is all of the amazing work that these folks are

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:08.219
doing to support researchers, and instead I want to focus on the documentation that

00:10:08.219 --> 00:10:11.140
makes it possible.

00:10:11.140 --> 00:10:19.219
So first of all, we have a place that researchers can go to to learn when to cloud, how to think

00:10:19.219 --> 00:10:24.099
about using the cloud with R and Python and other approaches.

00:10:24.099 --> 00:10:26.260
So this is the Earth Data Cloud Cookbook.

00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:27.619
It's made with Quarto.

00:10:27.619 --> 00:10:32.700
It's hosted on a GitHub repository that we're able to contribute to with Jupyter Notebooks

00:10:32.700 --> 00:10:35.419
and R Markdown documents and otherwise.

00:10:35.419 --> 00:10:41.020
But so this is the place that we started to have a place to contribute to.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:42.700
Our audience was really important.

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:47.739
We realized that it needed to be us first, and then specific researchers.

00:10:47.739 --> 00:10:52.520
And so this diagram shows that we really invested in our NASA OpenScapes mentor community in

00:10:52.520 --> 00:10:56.900
order to write documentation that would let us figure out how to use the cloud, and then

00:10:56.900 --> 00:11:02.500
we were able to then support other staff across the NASA data centers towards a specific workshop

00:11:02.580 --> 00:11:07.380
with researchers, and all the while contributing to the open science community through this

00:11:07.380 --> 00:11:09.900
documentation.

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:14.099
In terms of design, we're really emphasizing meeting people where they are.

00:11:14.099 --> 00:11:19.900
We don't assume experience with GitHub, with Quarto, with cloud, with Python, with R, with

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:25.940
Quarto, but we do have the expectation that everyone can learn and teach these things.

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:30.179
And so we're able to support folks coming from where they are and point them to the

00:11:30.179 --> 00:11:34.380
skills that they might need in order to contribute or learn.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:39.539
We're also able to collaborate on this documentation across workflows because we're using Quarto.

00:11:39.539 --> 00:11:44.820
We're able to share these or combine Jupyter Notebooks, R Markdown documents, as well as

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:51.059
contribute in our home places that we're most happy working, whether that's VS Code, Jupyter,

00:11:51.059 --> 00:11:54.619
RStudio, MATLAB, or otherwise.

00:11:54.619 --> 00:11:59.419
One other design element is that we're really reusing and complementing existing work.

00:11:59.419 --> 00:12:05.140
We found this documentation system framework is a really helpful way for us to write documentation.

00:12:05.140 --> 00:12:08.900
It helped us think about what was learning oriented and writing those as longer form

00:12:08.900 --> 00:12:14.659
tutorials versus what was problem oriented and could be quick how-to guides with copy

00:12:14.659 --> 00:12:18.440
and pasted code.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:21.940
Another part of complementing existing work and learning from others has been to be a

00:12:21.940 --> 00:12:25.299
part of the broader open science and open source community.

00:12:25.299 --> 00:12:31.059
This has really helped NASA mentors learn what's available, scope out what the bounds

00:12:31.059 --> 00:12:35.539
of the contribution around documentation should be, as well as co-develop and share and get

00:12:35.539 --> 00:12:39.659
that early feedback.

00:12:39.659 --> 00:12:40.659
What's possible from all of this?

00:12:40.659 --> 00:12:45.099
The amount of workshops that the NASA mentors have led and supported researchers who are

00:12:45.099 --> 00:12:51.820
now bringing their science to the cloud and able to leverage the capabilities has been

00:12:51.820 --> 00:12:52.820
really amazing.

00:12:53.340 --> 00:12:58.140
And again, I'll point you to the place where many of these mentors have been giving talks

00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:00.619
and supporting the researchers, which is awesome.

00:13:00.619 --> 00:13:05.179
I want to take it another level and talk about the documentation and process and where we're

00:13:05.179 --> 00:13:07.260
taking it from here.

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:12.140
So putting a focus on documentation has really enabled this NASA OpenScapes community to

00:13:12.140 --> 00:13:16.280
grow through intentional onboarding over the last three years.

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:21.780
So the point that we're really trying to build this sustainable community within NASA that's

00:13:21.780 --> 00:13:27.780
able to support researchers in the long term and have this documentation so that folks

00:13:27.780 --> 00:13:29.659
can contribute.

00:13:29.659 --> 00:13:34.460
So there's really been three places for three different audiences that has all been designed

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:39.700
for onboarding more NASA staff into this mentor community so that they're able to support

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:41.219
researchers.

00:13:41.219 --> 00:13:45.820
The first place is that we have a project website for NASA OpenScapes, and the primary

00:13:45.820 --> 00:13:50.659
audience is really for leadership and managers to have an idea of all of the work that the

00:13:50.659 --> 00:13:55.940
mentors are doing and really trying to make a lot of the invisible work more visible.

00:13:55.940 --> 00:14:01.299
We share all the slides and resources and workshops in one place so that there's visibility

00:14:01.299 --> 00:14:02.299
there.

00:14:02.299 --> 00:14:07.380
And really in terms of an onboarding idea for onboarding mentors, we're really there

00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:12.979
to invite participation and have that invitation and all the information that goes along with

00:14:12.979 --> 00:14:17.940
it, not live within a forwarded email, but actually have a place online that can be updated

00:14:17.940 --> 00:14:20.619
if necessary.

00:14:20.619 --> 00:14:24.859
The second place for onboarding mentors is actually in that Earth Data Cloud cookbook

00:14:24.859 --> 00:14:25.859
itself.

00:14:25.859 --> 00:14:29.739
We have a contributing section that was one of the earliest places that we developed,

00:14:29.739 --> 00:14:33.460
and that's really a welcome for new mentors once they join this community.

00:14:33.460 --> 00:14:37.900
That's where they learn how to access the communication channels we have on GitHub and

00:14:37.900 --> 00:14:44.460
Slack and JupyterHub, as well as all of the tech, as well as how to contribute and think

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:48.700
about how to do code review and pull requests and that kind of thing.

00:14:48.780 --> 00:14:53.580
And then we have a third place for onboarding, and that's really in our OpenScapes team approach

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:54.580
guide.

00:14:54.580 --> 00:14:59.340
This is where we kind of write documentation at this higher level for ourselves where we're

00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:03.179
thinking about our facilitation approaches, the purpose of doing the different things,

00:15:03.179 --> 00:15:05.099
our timelines, our checklists.

00:15:05.099 --> 00:15:11.299
And this has been the last thing that we have had the bandwidth to document, but we're dedicated

00:15:11.299 --> 00:15:13.859
to documenting this.

00:15:13.859 --> 00:15:20.619
So what's possible from all of this is that this mentor community is growing and taking

00:15:20.619 --> 00:15:25.219
more leadership of the community because they're able to not only repeat what we've done, but

00:15:25.219 --> 00:15:28.140
iterate and go beyond.

00:15:28.140 --> 00:15:33.940
And they're not having to start from scratch about timelines or onboarding text for emails

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:35.419
and whatnot.

00:15:35.419 --> 00:15:40.460
But beyond this, what's neat is that putting a focus on documentation has enabled NOAA

00:15:40.460 --> 00:15:47.500
fisheries, California water boards, and other groups to see this and repeat this whole process.

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:52.659
And this has all been just incredible and exciting work, but what's been neat is that

00:15:52.659 --> 00:15:58.340
the NASA OpenScapes mentors are part of this bigger cross-governmental group that are teaching

00:15:58.340 --> 00:16:04.619
each other, learning about what works and what doesn't work, and having a shared place

00:16:04.619 --> 00:16:06.119
to collaborate.

00:16:06.119 --> 00:16:11.479
So some of the advice that we have as this broader mentor community is to really invest

00:16:11.479 --> 00:16:18.559
in both technical and social infrastructure when you're thinking about how to document things.

00:16:18.559 --> 00:16:20.760
Documenting things will ultimately save time.

00:16:20.760 --> 00:16:24.760
There'll be fewer emails where people are emailing, asking where things are.

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:29.159
People will feel less stuck for the, well, they'll feel stuck for a shorter amount of

00:16:29.159 --> 00:16:30.400
times hopefully.

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:35.700
And they'll really feel less lost and like they belong.

00:16:35.700 --> 00:16:42.179
And that's a really critical thing just in general, but specifically during this pandemic

00:16:42.179 --> 00:16:44.780
and hybrid work culture.

00:16:44.780 --> 00:16:50.619
So this does, though, require intention and time, and this investment in psychological

00:16:50.619 --> 00:16:55.340
safety and growth mindset is really important for documenting things.

00:16:55.340 --> 00:17:03.500
So we have, yeah, I'll leave it there, but when you come back to thinking about documenting

00:17:03.500 --> 00:17:07.780
things openly for future us, it's have a place, have an audience in mind, and design

00:17:07.780 --> 00:17:10.380
for repeatability and accessibility.

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:12.500
So thanks so much.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:21.020
Thank you so much, Julia.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:26.219
So you mentioned several times that there are different levels of documentation, right?

00:17:26.219 --> 00:17:30.939
There are the technical stuff, there's the high-level stuff, and everything in between.

00:17:31.939 --> 00:17:37.339
What are the kind of recommendations you gave for getting it done, getting it on the ramp?

00:17:37.339 --> 00:17:40.660
Is it the same for all these kind of different documentation types?

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:43.780
That's a good question.

00:17:43.780 --> 00:17:52.780
For the teaching resources that the NASA OpenScapes mentors are putting together, that process

00:17:52.780 --> 00:17:55.420
is a bit more intentional.

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:58.339
Well, it's not a bit more intentional.

00:17:58.339 --> 00:17:59.339
It is more intentional.

00:17:59.739 --> 00:18:05.540
So it's done in a branch, we have dry runs, we review the materials, we test things in

00:18:05.540 --> 00:18:11.939
different places, and then that is merged back into the cookbook.

00:18:11.939 --> 00:18:22.619
When we're writing documentation on that higher level about what sort of Google Doc we should

00:18:22.619 --> 00:18:26.819
have in a one-on-one call, for example, that might be something that we kind of push to

00:18:26.819 --> 00:18:32.219
main pretty quickly, and I'm okay with that being a little messier, because it will still

00:18:32.219 --> 00:18:35.219
help future us on our team level.

00:18:35.219 --> 00:18:40.780
So yeah, there are different levels of review and quality assurance, absolutely, is the

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:41.780
short answer.

00:18:41.780 --> 00:18:42.780
Fantastic.

00:18:42.780 --> 00:18:49.459
So, as you said, documentation takes time, and it is something that gives back in a long

00:18:49.459 --> 00:18:50.900
time span.

00:18:50.900 --> 00:18:56.060
Can it be difficult to kind of allow management and other levels to carve out the time where

00:18:56.060 --> 00:19:01.579
you don't feel like you have to yourself prioritize it and make space for it?

00:19:01.579 --> 00:19:02.579
Yeah.

00:19:02.579 --> 00:19:10.859
Yeah, I think it's kind of a yes and approach, where the idea of showing what documentation

00:19:10.859 --> 00:19:12.099
can do is important.

00:19:12.099 --> 00:19:18.219
So if you take your messages from Slack and paste it into your Quarto book or your Google

00:19:18.219 --> 00:19:25.619
Doc, if you can show that to folks as being useful, that can help the second step of advocating

00:19:25.619 --> 00:19:27.180
for more time to document.

00:19:27.180 --> 00:19:32.780
But having that early thing to show that minimal viable product can be really helpful.

00:19:32.780 --> 00:19:37.459
But yeah, I think advocating for this as part of your time and part of your job is a big

00:19:37.459 --> 00:19:38.459
part of this.

00:19:38.459 --> 00:19:39.459
Fantastic.

00:19:39.459 --> 00:19:40.459
Thank you so much, Julia.

00:19:40.459 --> 00:19:41.459
Thank you.

00:19:41.459 --> 00:19:41.459


